\begin_layout Standard
I presented three projects under the umbrella of the Ocular Character Recognitio
n project at the MFA show.
 These were largely experiments with materiality and exploring how we engage
 with the digital and the process of taking a digital artifact and presenting
 it in a physical form.
 A CAPTCHA is something one rarely - if ever - encounters outside of a computer
 screen.
 While all of the pieces were generated and created through custom software,
 no software or computers were on display or shown as a part of the MFA
 show.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ocular Character Recognition consists of three separate, but related projects:
 Webpages for Humans - a web application used to CAPTCHA-fy
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
CAPTCHA-fy is the term I use to distort text to the point where it become
 unreadable by Optical Character Recognition.
 This technique is the only reason why CAPTCHAs work.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 machine-readable HTML documents; CAPTCHA-fy! - handmade booklets expressing
 the underlying goals and ideas under the OCR umbrella (a manifesto); and
 The Serendipity Engine - a modified printer used to serendipitously dispense/pr
oduce CAPTCHA-fied pages from eBooks digitized through Google's book/library
 project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
