\begin_layout Standard
The title Ocular Character Recognition is a play on the term Optical Character
 Recognition, which is the software used to convert scans or images of text
 into machine-readable documents.
 At its core, the process consists of recognizing glyphs within the pixels
 of an image and adding additional layers of metadata to that file in order
 to allow it to be searched and indexed.
 This is what adds the simple functionality of being able to select text
 from a scanned PDF.
 As opposed to an optical process - one which deals primarily with light
 and its properties - an ocular process implies an emphasis on the human
 eye.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, there are difficulties in the OCR process.
 OCR algorithms have difficulties with font changes, superscripts/subscripts,
 mathematical formulas, handwritten notes, or even full handwritten pages
 (journals, diaries, legal documents/letters)
